As an expert in calculus, I can tell you the range of the function  $f(x) = \sqrt{x^2}$ is determined by the nature of the square root function. 

The square root function always produces non-negative outputs. Since we're taking the square root of the square of *x*,  the input to the square root will always be non-negative.  

Therefore, the range of the function is all non-negative real numbers.

\begin{align*}
\boxed{[0, \infty)}
\end{align*}

